TASK 1: Update ORM models and seed reference data for new RBAC schema

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
CONTEXT
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
The database has been restructured to support a new RBAC model with
the following hierarchy:

  user → resources.group_idx → dpah_module_usergroups → dpah_modules
  user → dpah_user_roles → dpah_roles
  user(role + group) → dpah_role_agent_access → dpah_agents → dpah_collections → dpah_modules

Seven new tables exist (empty) with the `dpah_` prefix. The old tables
(roles, user_roles, collections, agents, role_agent_access,
role_collection_access) are NOT being used by this project anymore.
The old project on a different port still uses them; do not worry
about backward compatibility within this codebase.

═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
SCOPE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
1. Update app/models/db_schema.py:
   - Modify existing ORM classes to point at the new dpah_* tables
     and match the new column shapes:
       * Role             → __tablename__ = "dpah_roles"
       * UserRole         → __tablename__ = "dpah_user_roles"
       * Collection       → __tablename__ = "dpah_collections"
         (add module_id INT NOT NULL; remove `department` if present)
       * Agent            → __tablename__ = "dpah_agents"
         (add collection_id INT NOT NULL;
          add persona column — values CREATOR/REVIEWER/APPROVER;
          keep department for now)
       * RoleAgentAccess  → __tablename__ = "dpah_role_agent_access"
         (change composite PK from (role_id, agent_id) to
          (role_id, group_id, agent_id); add group_id INT NOT NULL)
   - REMOVE the RoleCollectionAccess ORM class entirely (no longer
     used; access is now expressed via agents only).
   - ADD two new ORM classes:
       * Module           → __tablename__ = "dpah_modules"
       * ModuleUserGroup  → __tablename__ = "dpah_module_usergroups"
   - ADD `group_idx` (INT) column to the Resource ORM class. Do not
     run any migration on the `resources` table — the column already
     exists in the database. Just reflect it in the ORM.

2. Create scripts/seed_dpah_tables.py:
   An idempotent Python script that uses the existing SQLAlchemy
   session from app/dao/database.py to populate seed data. Idempotent
   means: running it twice produces the same result; do NOT use
   raw INSERT — use ORM upserts (check-then-insert or merge).

   Seed the following (use the existing SessionLocal from
   app/dao/database.py):

   dpah_roles:
     - id=7, name="Junior",  description="Junior level"
     - id=8, name="Mid",     description="Mid level"
     - id=9, name="Senior",  description="Senior level"

   dpah_modules:
     - id=1, name="RMS",     description="Resource Management System"
     - id=2, name="SCM",     description="Supply Chain Management"
     - id=3, name="HRMS",    description="Human Resource Management"
     - id=4, name="FINANCE", description="Finance"
     - id=5, name="MRR",     description="Material Requisition"
     (set created_by="system", updated_by="system")

   dpah_collections (module_id → collection_name):
     - RMS:     rms_timesheet, rms_projectplan
     - SCM:     scm_potracker, scm_electronics
     - HRMS:    hrms_leave_data, hrms_salarydata
     - FINANCE: finance_general
     - MRR:     mrr_general

   dpah_agents:
  For EACH collection above, create 3 agent rows — one per persona.
  Naming convention: {MODULE}_{COLLECTION_SUFFIX}_{PERSONA}
  The persona is encoded ONLY in the agent_name suffix (last
  underscore-separated segment). No separate persona column exists.
  Examples:
    - RMS_TIMESHEET_CREATOR
    - RMS_TIMESHEET_REVIEWER
    - RMS_TIMESHEET_APPROVER
    - RMS_PROJECTPLAN_CREATOR
    - ... and so on for all collections.
  Set:
    - department    = None (NULL)
    - description   = "Auto-seeded agent for {collection}"
    - system_prompt = None
    - allowed_tools = None
    - model_name    = "claude-sonnet-4"
    - collection_id = id of the corresponding collection row
    - is_active     = 1

   dpah_module_usergroups:
     Map at least 2 distinct group_idx values to modules:
       - group_idx=1 → RMS, HRMS         (Operations group)
       - group_idx=2 → FINANCE, SCM, MRR (Finance/SCM group)
       - group_idx=3 → RMS, SCM, HRMS, FINANCE, MRR (All — admin group)
     (set is_active=1, assigned_by="system")

   dpah_role_agent_access:
     Insert sample (role_id, group_id, agent_id) triples covering at
     least these scenarios:
       - Junior (7) in group 1: gets only CREATOR persona for RMS &
         HRMS collections.
       - Mid (8) in group 1: gets CREATOR + REVIEWER for RMS & HRMS.
       - Senior (9) in group 1: gets all three personas for RMS & HRMS.
       - Senior (9) in group 3: gets all three personas for all
         collections in all modules (admin).
     (set granted_by="system")

3. Create scripts/README.md with a single short paragraph explaining:
   - What the seed script does
   - How to run it (python -m scripts.seed_dpah_tables from project root)
   - That it's idempotent and safe to re-run

